{"title_page": "Prelude, Op. 74, No. 2 (Scriabin)", "text_new": "[[Alexander Scriabin]]'s '''Prelude, Op. 74, No. 2''', entitled '''Tr\u00e8s lent, contemplatif''' (very slow, contemplating), is one of five preludes in Op. 74, composed in late 1914.\n\nHis second wife considered it his best piece.<ref>Leonid Sabaneev: Erinnerungen an Alexander Skrjabin. ''Verlag Ernst Kuhn'' 1925/2005. (p 354) {{ISBN|3-928864-21-1}}</ref> It was also his last, for Scriabin died soon after.\n\n[[Leonid Sabaneyev]] cites the composer with the following words: \"These [[Quartal and quintal harmony|quint]]s are really creating a totally new sentiment, don't you think? [...] These harmonies are less resonant here, but look how highly psychologically difficult it has become. [...] Here reigns a blazing heat like in the [astral] desert. [...] and here again this longing urge [he played the chromatically descending melody line] [...] You know, this Prelude gives the impression as if it would last for centuries, even eternally, millions of years.\" - \"The piece can be played in two ways. Either coloured by manifold nuances, or, quite the opposite, completely uniform, without the least shading. [...] in one single piece, there are multiple ones laid out, a multiplicity of the composition.\" - \"Until now I always composed so that the interpretation of a piece was only possible in one way [...] Now I want it to be possible to be played in totally different ways, like a crystal can reflect totally different rays of light.\" - He said, quietly and hauntingly, \"This is death! This is death as this emanation of the female which leads to unification [...] death and love [...] this is the abyss.\" This is not music\", said [Sabaneev] to him, \"this is something else...\" - \"This is the [[Mysterium (Scriabin)|Mysterium]],\" he said softly.<ref>Leonid Sabaneev: Erinnerungen an Alexander Skrjabin. ''Verlag Ernst Kuhn'' 1925/2005. (p 351) {{ISBN|3-928864-21-1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMSLP2|work=5_Preludes%2C_Op.74_(Scriabin%2C_Alexander)|cname=Preludes Op. 74 (Scriabin)}}\n\n{{Alexander Scriabin}}\n\n[[Category:Preludes by Alexander Scriabin]]\n[[Category:1914 compositions]]\n\n{{classical-composition-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[Alexander Scriabin]]'s '''Prelude, Op. 74, No. 2''', entitled '''Tr\u00e8s lent, contemplatif''' (very slow, contemplating), is one of five preludes in Op. 74, composed in early 1915.\n\nHis second wife considered it his best piece.<ref>Leonid Sabaneev: Erinnerungen an Alexander Skrjabin. ''Verlag Ernst Kuhn'' 1925/2005. (p 354) {{ISBN|3-928864-21-1}}</ref> It was also his last, for Scriabin died soon after.\n\n[[Leonid Sabaneyev]] cites the composer with the following words: \"These [[Quartal and quintal harmony|quint]]s are really creating a totally new sentiment, don't you think? [...] These harmonies are less resonant here, but look how highly psychologically difficult it has become. [...] Here reigns a blazing heat like in the [astral] desert. [...] and here again this longing urge [he played the chromatically descending melody line] [...] You know, this Prelude gives the impression as if it would last for centuries, even eternally, millions of years.\" - \"The piece can be played in two ways. Either coloured by manifold nuances, or, quite the opposite, completely uniform, without the least shading. [...] in one single piece, there are multiple ones laid out, a multiplicity of the composition.\" - \"Until now I always composed so that the interpretation of a piece was only possible in one way [...] Now I want it to be possible to be played in totally different ways, like a crystal can reflect totally different rays of light.\" - He said, quietly and hauntingly, \"This is death! This is death as this emanation of the female which leads to unification [...] death and love [...] this is the abyss.\" This is not music\", said [Sabaneev] to him, \"this is something else...\" - \"This is the [[Mysterium (Scriabin)|Mysterium]],\" he said softly.<ref>Leonid Sabaneev: Erinnerungen an Alexander Skrjabin. ''Verlag Ernst Kuhn'' 1925/2005. (p 351) {{ISBN|3-928864-21-1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMSLP2|work=5_Preludes%2C_Op.74_(Scriabin%2C_Alexander)|cname=Preludes Op. 74 (Scriabin)}}\n\n{{Alexander Scriabin}}\n\n[[Category:Preludes by Alexander Scriabin]]\n[[Category:1914 compositions]]\n\n{{classical-composition-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pianoman598", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prelude,_Op._74,_No._2_(Scriabin)"}
{"title_page": "A Primitive Evolution", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = A Primitive Evolution\n| image = APE 2014 Promo.jpg\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| years_active = 2007\u2013present\n| genre = [[Alternative rock]], [[Death Rock]]\n| associated_acts = [[The Birthday Massacre]], Lye, Aphasia\n| label = None\n| website = [http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com/ www.aprimitiveevolution.com]\n| current_members = Brett Carruthers<br>Steph Misayo Seki<br>Stu Dead\n| past_members = Scott Carruthers<br>Dimitri Anastasakis<br>[[Rhim]]\n}}\n\n'''A Primitive Evolution''' (often identified using the abbreviation '''A.P.E.''') is an [[alternative rock]] band based in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation===\nFormed in the Fall of 2007 out of band Lye (and before that Aphasia), vocalist Brett Carruthers and bassist Stephany Seki began jamming with drummer Stu Dead, founder of Playdead Cult, a clothing brand and creative lifestyle house located in Toronto. Playdead's involvement in horror culture led to inviting the owner of Darkside horror shop's Dimitri Anastasakis to jam along on guitar. With this line up, they first publicly performed for Toronto's Queen Street Fire fundraiser alongside [[Billy Talent]] and [[The Creepshow]].<ref>[http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Lowdown/2008/03/13/4992346-ca.html Canoe.ca article \"Billy Talent, Alexis aid fire victims\"].</ref><ref>[http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/news/local/article/21474--billy-talent-to-headline-fundraiser-for-queen-west-fire-victims CityTV article \"Billy Talent To Headline Fundraiser For Queen West Fire Victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629154250/http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/news/local/article/21474--billy-talent-to-headline-fundraiser-for-queen-west-fire-victims |date=June 29, 2011 }}.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, The band self-produced the video for \"Death on Wheels\" <ref>{{cite web|title=Death On Wheels by A Primitive Evolution Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rJtAkjAOIv0|publisher=A Primitive Evolution|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> alongside Frankenstein cheerleaders as part of the 2007 [[L'Or\u00e9al]] Fashion Week,<ref>{{cite web|title=L'Oreal Fashion Week|url=http://www.lgfashionweek.ca/|publisher=L'Oreal|accessdate=August 11, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110716031801/http://lgfashionweek.ca/| archivedate= July 16, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref> which was voiced by [[Martin Streek]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Death on Wheels- A Primitive Evolution \u2013 With Voice-Over by Martin Streek|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h2SokjUDSnc|publisher=A Primitive Evolution|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> \"Death on Wheels\" would initiate, The Death Girls, cheerleaders and super-fans that dance and sing at A.P.E events, sometimes by joining the band on stage. Notable Death Girls include models from the adult website [[Suicide Girls]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution Biography|url=http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com/fr_home.cfm|publisher=APrimitiveEvolution.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> A Primitive Evolution would later appear on the adult news channel, [[Naked News]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution on Naked News (censored)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OL-PCYydpk|publisher=Naked News|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> \"Death on Wheels\" was also featured on [[Alan Cross]]'s \"Five Songs You Gotta Hear Today\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Songs You Gotta Hear for March 25, 2010|url=http://exploremusic.com/show/five-songs-you-gotta-hear-for-march-25-2010/|publisher=Exploremusic.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, A Primitive Evolution played a [[Canadian Music Week]] showcase at [[Bovine Sex Club|The Bovine Sex Club]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CMW Preview: A Primitive Evolution|url=http://www.torontomusicscene.ca/interviews/cmw-preview-a-primitive-evolution.html|publisher=torontomusicscene.ca|accessdate=11 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001230427/http://www.torontomusicscene.ca/interviews/cmw-preview-a-primitive-evolution.html|archive-date=October 1, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2008 the band continued writing and recording their debut album and worked on another music video for the song \"Beyond True\". In May they posted a demo for the song \"Empty Holes\", which would later also have a corresponding music video. Brett said in a 2010 interview that during these early years the band worked \"just writing and figuring each other out\".<ref>{{cite video| people= Katherine Curtis, Brett Carruthers, Dimitri Anastasakis, Stephany Seki, Stu Dead| date= Jan 12, 2010| title= A Primitive Evolution on Naked News (censored) | url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OL-PCYydpk| medium= Video| publisher= Naked News | time= 0:50}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2009 the group founded the music festival VIVA LOS MUERTOS (2009 line-up featuring [[The Birthday Massacre]], for whom Brett had performed live keyboards for during their Fall 2004 tour).<ref>{{cite web|title=Terrorverlag.de Interview with Chibi and Rainbow \u2013 2004|url=http://www.musik.terrorverlag.de/interviews.php?id=176}}</ref> The festival included \"Major merch sales, dancing Playdead [[mascots]] and an eclectic long-weekend crowd that collectively offered plenty for the live eye\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/entertainment/music/article/10792--in-photos-viva-los-muertos-at-the-mod-club |title=CityTV article \"In Photos: Viva Los Muertos! At The Mod Club\" |access-date=October 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629154303/http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/entertainment/music/article/10792--in-photos-viva-los-muertos-at-the-mod-club |archive-date=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The festival had an \"overwhelmingly good response\", according to the band, hoping to further secure the creation and maintenance of a dynamic \"[[Death Rock]]\" scene in Toronto. Playdead Cult's \"Moop\", would continue to be the band's mascot and can be seen dancing on stage during the band's live performances.\n\nLater on in 2009, the band's self-produced debut video for \"Death on Wheels\", voiced by veteran Toronto radio DJ Martin Streek,<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/arts/media/story/2009/07/07/martin-streek.html CBC article \"Toronto DJ Martin Streek dead at 45\"].</ref> caught the attention of the production crew for the vampire musical movie [[Suck (film)|Suck]].<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/14844/94438 Rolling Stone article \"Moby Sucks It Up Alongside Iggy Pop, Alice Cooper in Vampire Flick\"].</ref> This film debuted at the 2009 [[Toronto International Film Festival]] featured the likes of [[Iggy Pop]], [[Alice Cooper]] and [[Henry Rollins]] The film consequently utilized the band's rehearsal space<ref>[http://www.suckthemovie.com/photos.html Suck the Movie photo gallery] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129201016/http://suckthemovie.com/photos.html |date=November 29, 2010 }}.</ref> as a set for several scenes in the film. Finally at the end of 2009 the band would release their self-titled debut album.\n\nFebruary 16, 2010, the band released their debut album digitally for worldwide distribution. In the summer of 2010, Adm Shedden, formerly of The Birthday Massacre and currently of Hunter Eves, joined to perform on live violin for acoustic shows. In 2010, the band continued playing shows in Toronto, [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]], [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]] and [[Barrie, Ontario|Barrie]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution \u2013 Past tour dates|url=http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com/fr_tour.cfm|publisher=aprimitiveevolution.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2011, the band posted on their [[Facebook]] profile that Scott Carruthers (Brett's cousin), would replace Dimitri Anastasakis on guitar. Dimitri had announced in the fall of 2010 also on their [[Facebook]] profile that he would be leaving the band due to pursue other goals important to his life. In 2011, the band recorded a new acoustic album, co-produced by [[Marcy Playground|John Wozniak]], and welcomed back their friend, Adm Shedden for violin. The band encouraged fans to participate in its development by listening to rough mixes.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution: The Acoustic Album : Updates|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/aprimitiveevolution/updates/5841|publisher=Pledgemusic|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> The band documented the recording process with video, [[MP3]]'s and photo updates on their official website and also announced that 20% of the proceeds would be donated to [[ShelterBox]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution: The Acoustic Album|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/aprimitiveevolution|publisher=Pledgemusic|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> In July, the band performed at Trash Fest USA, in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Trash Fest USA|url=http://www.mamatrash.com/trashfestus.htm|publisher=Trash Fest USA|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> A Primitive Evolution was recommended by [[George Stroumboulopoulos]] for Canadian Music Week 2011 in his Top 3 Buzz Bands out of the 800 that performed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Music Week|url=http://www.cbc.ca/strombo/show-music/canadian-music-week.html|publisher=CBC|accessdate=August 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the band signed a record deal with [[Metropolis Records]] to release their album ''Becoming''. Now acting as a three piece with Brett Carruthers, Stephany Seki and Stu Dead, this would be the band's debut release under an official label.<ref>https://www.rue-morgue.com/exclusive-new-video-from-a-primitive-evolutions-forthcoming-album-becoming/</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===''A.P.E.'' (2009)===\nThe band's debut album ''A.P.E.'', released in early December 2009,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bringbacktheboombox.com/main/interviews/fuck-everything-that-anyone-has-ever-told-you-to-do-a-p-e-interview/ |title=Bring Back the Boom Box interview |access-date=October 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301061552/http://bringbacktheboombox.com/main/interviews/fuck-everything-that-anyone-has-ever-told-you-to-do-a-p-e-interview/ |archive-date=March 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> was produced by [[Alpha Galates|Matthew Von Wagner]], ([[Crystal Castles (band)|Crystal Castles]], [[Ubiquitous Synergy Seeker]], [[Alpha Galates]]) and Brett Carruthers. Wagner has worked alongside the likes of [[Joe Barresi]] and [[Bob Ludwig]]. ''A.P.E.'', according to the band, is grounded on a few common themes: the single \"Death on Wheels\" draws inspiration from classic [[grindhouse]] horror films, while others like \"Dead End\" are thinly veiled love songs. \"War B.\" explores political undertones and the Western view of war. Other songs on the album like \"Beyond True\" explore the [[romanticism]] of human interaction.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Alan Cross]] has referenced the band to sound like [[Radiohead]] and [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and would go on to call them [[The Offspring]] of [[Grunge]] in his May 21, 2010, ExploreMusic podcast. (searchable on iTunes) <ref>{{cite web|title=Song of the day give away|url=http://exploremusic.com/indie-track/a-primitive-evolution-beyond-true/|publisher=Exploremusic.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Tracks====\n# \"War B\" (4:40)\n# \"Beyond True\" (4:19)\n# \"Death on Wheels\" (4:02)\n# \"Just Begun\" (4:59)\n# \"Dead End\" (3:59)\n# \"Still Waiting\" (4:26)\n# \"Coming and Going\" (3:03)\n# \"Show Me\" (4:41)\n# \"Train Wreck\" (4:45)\n# \"To Be Lost\" (5:17)\n# \"Empty Holes\" (4:27)\n\n===''The Prize'' (2012)===\n\nThe band's sophomore album ''The Prize'' was released on September 11, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://music-news.com/review/UK/8941/Read|title=A Primitive Evolution|website=Music-News.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref> ''The Prize'' still includes reworked versions of songs found on APE's debut, but also features three new songs. The album was produced by the band and [[John Wozniak]] of [[Marcy Playground]] at Mushroom studios in Toronto, ON.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://punkglobe.com/aprimitiveevolutionreview0513.php|title=A Primitive Evolution|website=punkglobe.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref>\n\n====Tracks====\n# \"Lord Of Reason\" (4:05)\n# \"Show Me\" (The Prize Version) (3:52)\n# \"I Feel It All\" (4:52)\n# \"Won't Let You Down\" (4:10)\n# \"Falling Far Behind\" (4:28)\n# \"Dead End\" (The Prize Version) (3:59)\n# \"The Prize\" (4:26)\n# \"Coming and Going\" (The Prize Version) (3:05)\n# \"Train Wreck\" (The Prize Version) (5:36)\n# \"We Are Lost\" (4:31)\n\n===''Becoming'' (2018)===\n\nThe band's third album ''Becoming'' was released on October 5th, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rue-morgue.com/exclusive-new-video-from-a-primitive-evolutions-forthcoming-album-becoming|title=EXCLUSIVE: NEW VIDEO FROM A PRIMITIVE EVOLUTION\u2019S FORTHCOMING ALBUM, \u201cBECOMING\u201d|website=rue-morgue.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> Recorded at their self-built Desolation Studios in Toronto, Becoming features many exciting Canadian collaborations including writer/producer [[Ian D\u2019Sa]] from [[Billy Talent]] and audio engineer [[Kenny Luong]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metropolis-records.com/product/11638/becoming|title=A Primitive Evolution - Becoming|website=metropolis-records.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref>\n\n====Tracks====\n# \"I am an Infinite Cycle\" (1:16)\n# \"Who's Your Maker\" (4:47)\n# \"The Beauty\" (4:19)\n# \"Close Your Eyes\" (4:11)\n# \"Ghost\" (6:17)\n# \"Dead Skies\" (5:22)\n# \"We Are The Truth\" (4:38)\n# \"Becoming\" (3:56)\n# \"Skeleton\" (4:50)\n# \"Picturesque Hell\" (4:28)\n# \"Better Off Dead\" (5:09)\n# \"Live Forever\" (5:05)\n# \"Echo\" (5:38)\n\n==Members==\n*Brett Carruthers &ndash; [[Electric guitar|guitar]]s, [[Singing|vocals]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]]s <small>(2007&ndash;present)</small>\n*Steph Misayo Seki &ndash; [[Bass guitar|bass]], keyboards, [[cello]] <small>(2007&ndash;present)</small>\n*Stu Dead &ndash; [[Drum kit|drums]] <small>(2007&ndash;present)</small>\n\n===Touring members===\n*[[The Birthday Massacre|Owen Mackinder]] &ndash; keyboards <small>(2019&ndash;present)</small>\n*Jake Hamilton &ndash; drums <small>(2019)</small>\n\n===Former members===\n*Dimitri Anastasakis &ndash; [[lead guitar]] <small>(2007&ndash;2010)</small>\n*Scott Carruthers &ndash; lead guitar <small>(2011&ndash;2013)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com}}\n*[http://www.playdeadcult.com Playdead Cult]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110319020047/http://www.thedarksidestore.com/ The Darkside Store]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Primitive Evolution}}\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Canadian alternative rock groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Toronto]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = A Primitive Evolution\n| image = APE 2014 Promo.jpg\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| years_active = 2007\u2013present\n| genre = [[Alternative rock]], [[Death Rock]]\n| associated_acts = [[The Birthday Massacre]], Lye, Aphasia\n| label = None\n| website = [http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com/ www.aprimitiveevolution.com]\n| current_members = Brett Carruthers<br>Steph Misayo Seki<br>Stu Dead\n| past_members = Scott Carruthers<br>Dimitri Anastasakis<br>[[Rhim]]\n}}\n\n'''A Primitive Evolution''' (often identified using the abbreviation '''A.P.E.''') is an [[alternative rock]] band based in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation===\nFormed in the Fall of 2007 out of band Lye (and before that Aphasia), vocalist Brett Carruthers and bassist Stephany Seki began jamming with drummer Stu Dead, founder of Playdead Cult, a clothing brand and creative lifestyle house located in Toronto. Playdead's involvement in horror culture led to inviting the owner of Darkside horror shop's Dimitri Anastasakis to jam along on guitar. With this line up, they first publicly performed for Toronto's Queen Street Fire fundraiser alongside [[Billy Talent]] and [[The Creepshow]].<ref>[http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Lowdown/2008/03/13/4992346-ca.html Canoe.ca article \"Billy Talent, Alexis aid fire victims\"].</ref><ref>[http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/news/local/article/21474--billy-talent-to-headline-fundraiser-for-queen-west-fire-victims CityTV article \"Billy Talent To Headline Fundraiser For Queen West Fire Victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629154250/http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/news/local/article/21474--billy-talent-to-headline-fundraiser-for-queen-west-fire-victims |date=June 29, 2011 }}.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, The band self-produced the video for \"Death on Wheels\" <ref>{{cite web|title=Death On Wheels by A Primitive Evolution Official Music Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rJtAkjAOIv0|publisher=A Primitive Evolution|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> alongside Frankenstein cheerleaders as part of the 2007 [[L'Or\u00e9al]] Fashion Week,<ref>{{cite web|title=L'Oreal Fashion Week|url=http://www.lgfashionweek.ca/|publisher=L'Oreal|accessdate=August 11, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110716031801/http://lgfashionweek.ca/| archivedate= July 16, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref> which was voiced by [[Martin Streek]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Death on Wheels- A Primitive Evolution \u2013 With Voice-Over by Martin Streek|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h2SokjUDSnc|publisher=A Primitive Evolution|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> \"Death on Wheels\" would initiate, The Death Girls, cheerleaders and super-fans that dance and sing at A.P.E events, sometimes by joining the band on stage. Notable Death Girls include models from the adult website [[Suicide Girls]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution Biography|url=http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com/fr_home.cfm|publisher=APrimitiveEvolution.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> A Primitive Evolution would later appear on the adult news channel, [[Naked News]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution on Naked News (censored)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OL-PCYydpk|publisher=Naked News|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> \"Death on Wheels\" was also featured on [[Alan Cross]]'s \"Five Songs You Gotta Hear Today\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Songs You Gotta Hear for March 25, 2010|url=http://exploremusic.com/show/five-songs-you-gotta-hear-for-march-25-2010/|publisher=Exploremusic.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, A Primitive Evolution played a [[Canadian Music Week]] showcase at [[Bovine Sex Club|The Bovine Sex Club]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CMW Preview: A Primitive Evolution|url=http://www.torontomusicscene.ca/interviews/cmw-preview-a-primitive-evolution.html|publisher=torontomusicscene.ca|accessdate=11 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001230427/http://www.torontomusicscene.ca/interviews/cmw-preview-a-primitive-evolution.html|archive-date=October 1, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2008 the band continued writing and recording their debut album and worked on another music video for the song \"Beyond True\". In May they posted a demo for the song \"Empty Holes\", which would later also have a corresponding music video. Brett said in a 2010 interview that during these early years the band worked \"just writing and figuring each other out\".<ref>{{cite video| people= Katherine Curtis, Brett Carruthers, Dimitri Anastasakis, Stephany Seki, Stu Dead| date= Jan 12, 2010| title= A Primitive Evolution on Naked News (censored) | url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OL-PCYydpk| medium= Video| publisher= Naked News | time= 0:50}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2009 the group founded the music festival VIVA LOS MUERTOS (2009 line-up featuring [[The Birthday Massacre]], for whom Brett had performed live keyboards for during their Fall 2004 tour).<ref>{{cite web|title=Terrorverlag.de Interview with Chibi and Rainbow \u2013 2004|url=http://www.musik.terrorverlag.de/interviews.php?id=176}}</ref> The festival included \"Major merch sales, dancing Playdead [[mascots]] and an eclectic long-weekend crowd that collectively offered plenty for the live eye\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/entertainment/music/article/10792--in-photos-viva-los-muertos-at-the-mod-club |title=CityTV article \"In Photos: Viva Los Muertos! At The Mod Club\" |access-date=October 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629154303/http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/entertainment/music/article/10792--in-photos-viva-los-muertos-at-the-mod-club |archive-date=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The festival had an \"overwhelmingly good response\", according to the band, hoping to further secure the creation and maintenance of a dynamic \"[[Death Rock]]\" scene in Toronto. Playdead Cult's \"Moop\", would continue to be the band's mascot and can be seen dancing on stage during the band's live performances.\n\nLater on in 2009, the band's self-produced debut video for \"Death on Wheels\", voiced by veteran Toronto radio DJ Martin Streek,<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/arts/media/story/2009/07/07/martin-streek.html CBC article \"Toronto DJ Martin Streek dead at 45\"].</ref> caught the attention of the production crew for the vampire musical movie [[Suck (film)|Suck]].<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/14844/94438 Rolling Stone article \"Moby Sucks It Up Alongside Iggy Pop, Alice Cooper in Vampire Flick\"].</ref> This film debuted at the 2009 [[Toronto International Film Festival]] featured the likes of [[Iggy Pop]], [[Alice Cooper]] and [[Henry Rollins]] The film consequently utilized the band's rehearsal space<ref>[http://www.suckthemovie.com/photos.html Suck the Movie photo gallery] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129201016/http://suckthemovie.com/photos.html |date=November 29, 2010 }}.</ref> as a set for several scenes in the film. Finally at the end of 2009 the band would release their self-titled debut album.\n\nFebruary 16, 2010, the band released their debut album digitally for worldwide distribution. In the summer of 2010, Adm Shedden, formerly of The Birthday Massacre and currently of Hunter Eves, joined to perform on live violin for acoustic shows. In 2010, the band continued playing shows in Toronto, [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]], [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]] and [[Barrie, Ontario|Barrie]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution \u2013 Past tour dates|url=http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com/fr_tour.cfm|publisher=aprimitiveevolution.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2011, the band posted on their [[Facebook]] profile that Scott Carruthers (Brett's cousin), would replace Dimitri Anastasakis on guitar. Dimitri had announced in the fall of 2010 also on their [[Facebook]] profile that he would be leaving the band due to pursue other goals important to his life. In 2011, the band recorded a new acoustic album, co-produced by [[Marcy Playground|John Wozniak]], and welcomed back their friend, Adm Shedden for violin. The band encouraged fans to participate in its development by listening to rough mixes.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution: The Acoustic Album : Updates|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/aprimitiveevolution/updates/5841|publisher=Pledgemusic|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> The band documented the recording process with video, [[MP3]]'s and photo updates on their official website and also announced that 20% of the proceeds would be donated to [[ShelterBox]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Primitive Evolution: The Acoustic Album|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/aprimitiveevolution|publisher=Pledgemusic|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> In July, the band performed at Trash Fest USA, in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Trash Fest USA|url=http://www.mamatrash.com/trashfestus.htm|publisher=Trash Fest USA|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> A Primitive Evolution was recommended by [[George Stroumboulopoulos]] for Canadian Music Week 2011 in his Top 3 Buzz Bands out of the 800 that performed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Music Week|url=http://www.cbc.ca/strombo/show-music/canadian-music-week.html|publisher=CBC|accessdate=August 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the band signed a record deal with [[Metropolis Records]] to release their album ''Becoming''. Now acting as a three piece with Brett Carruthers, Stephany Seki and Stu Dead, this would be the band's debut release under an official label.<ref>https://www.rue-morgue.com/exclusive-new-video-from-a-primitive-evolutions-forthcoming-album-becoming/</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===''A.P.E.'' (2009)===\nThe band's debut album ''A.P.E.'', released in early December 2009,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bringbacktheboombox.com/main/interviews/fuck-everything-that-anyone-has-ever-told-you-to-do-a-p-e-interview/ |title=Bring Back the Boom Box interview |access-date=October 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301061552/http://bringbacktheboombox.com/main/interviews/fuck-everything-that-anyone-has-ever-told-you-to-do-a-p-e-interview/ |archive-date=March 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> was produced by [[Alpha Galates|Matthew Von Wagner]], ([[Crystal Castles (band)|Crystal Castles]], [[Ubiquitous Synergy Seeker]], [[Alpha Galates]]) and Brett Carruthers. Wagner has worked alongside the likes of [[Joe Barresi]] and [[Bob Ludwig]]. ''A.P.E.'', according to the band, is grounded on a few common themes: the single \"Death on Wheels\" draws inspiration from classic [[grindhouse]] horror films, while others like \"Dead End\" are thinly veiled love songs. \"War B.\" explores political undertones and the Western view of war. Other songs on the album like \"Beyond True\" explore the [[romanticism]] of human interaction.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Alan Cross]] has referenced the band to sound like [[Radiohead]] and [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and would go on to call them [[The Offspring]] of [[Grunge]] in his May 21, 2010, ExploreMusic podcast. (searchable on iTunes) <ref>{{cite web|title=Song of the day give away|url=http://exploremusic.com/indie-track/a-primitive-evolution-beyond-true/|publisher=Exploremusic.com|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Tracks====\n# \"War B\" (4:40)\n# \"Beyond True\" (4:19)\n# \"Death on Wheels\" (4:02)\n# \"Just Begun\" (4:59)\n# \"Dead End\" (3:59)\n# \"Still Waiting\" (4:26)\n# \"Coming and Going\" (3:03)\n# \"Show Me\" (4:41)\n# \"Train Wreck\" (4:45)\n# \"To Be Lost\" (5:17)\n# \"Empty Holes\" (4:27)\n\n===''The Prize'' (2012)===\n\nThe band's sophomore album ''The Prize'' was released on September 11, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://music-news.com/review/UK/8941/Read|title=A Primitive Evolution|website=Music-News.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref> ''The Prize'' still includes reworked versions of songs found on APE's debut, but also features three new songs. The album was produced by the band and [[John Wozniak]] of [[Marcy Playground]] at Mushroom studios in Toronto, ON.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://punkglobe.com/aprimitiveevolutionreview0513.php|title=A Primitive Evolution|website=punkglobe.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-07}}</ref>\n\n====Tracks====\n# \"Lord Of Reason\" (4:05)\n# \"Show Me\" (The Prize Version) (3:52)\n# \"I Feel It All\" (4:52)\n# \"Won't Let You Down\" (4:10)\n# \"Falling Far Behind\" (4:28)\n# \"Dead End\" (The Prize Version) (3:59)\n# \"The Prize\" (4:26)\n# \"Coming and Going\" (The Prize Version) (3:05)\n# \"Train Wreck\" (The Prize Version) (5:36)\n# \"We Are Lost\" (4:31)\n\n===''Becoming'' (2018)===\n\nThe band's third album ''Becoming'' was released on October 5th, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rue-morgue.com/exclusive-new-video-from-a-primitive-evolutions-forthcoming-album-becoming|title=EXCLUSIVE: NEW VIDEO FROM A PRIMITIVE EVOLUTION\u2019S FORTHCOMING ALBUM, \u201cBECOMING\u201d}}</ref> Recorded at their self-built Desolation Studios in Toronto, Becoming features many exciting Canadian collaborations including writer/producer [[Ian D\u2019Sa]] from [[Billy Talent]] and audio engineer [[Kenny Luong]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metropolis-records.com/product/11638/becoming|title=A Primitive Evolution - Becoming|website=metropolis-records.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref>\n\n====Tracks====\n# \"I am an Infinite Cycle\" (1:16)\n# \"Who's Your Maker\" (4:47)\n# \"The Beauty\" (4:19)\n# \"Close Your Eyes\" (4:11)\n# \"Ghost\" (6:17)\n# \"Dead Skies\" (5:22)\n# \"We Are The Truth\" (4:38)\n# \"Becoming\" (3:56)\n# \"Skeleton\" (4:50)\n# \"Picturesque Hell\" (4:28)\n# \"Better Off Dead\" (5:09)\n# \"Live Forever\" (5:05)\n# \"Echo\" (5:38)\n\n==Members==\n*Brett Carruthers &ndash; [[Electric guitar|guitar]]s, [[Singing|vocals]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]]s <small>(2007&ndash;present)</small>\n*Steph Misayo Seki &ndash; [[Bass guitar|bass]], keyboards, [[cello]] <small>(2007&ndash;present)</small>\n*Stu Dead &ndash; [[Drum kit|drums]] <small>(2007&ndash;present)</small>\n\n===Touring members===\n*[[The Birthday Massacre|Owen Mackinder]] &ndash; keyboards <small>(2019&ndash;present)</small>\n*Jake Hamilton &ndash; drums <small>(2019)</small>\n\n===Former members===\n*Dimitri Anastasakis &ndash; [[lead guitar]] <small>(2007&ndash;2010)</small>\n*Scott Carruthers &ndash; lead guitar <small>(2011&ndash;2013)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.aprimitiveevolution.com}}\n*[http://www.playdeadcult.com Playdead Cult]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110319020047/http://www.thedarksidestore.com/ The Darkside Store]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Primitive Evolution}}\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Canadian alternative rock groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Toronto]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Brettcarruthers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBecoming (2018)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Primitive_Evolution"}
{"title_page": "SEPTA subway\u2013surface trolley lines", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Green Line (Philadelphia)|other green lines|Green Line (disambiguation){{!}}Green Line|the proposed rail system|Greenline (Pennsylvania)}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name = Subway\u2013surface trolley lines<br><small>Routes 10, 11, 13, 34, 36</small>\n<!-- Styles ----- ----- -->\n| box_width = auto\n| color = {{rcr|SEPTA|Subway-Surface}}\n<!-- Images ----- ----- -->\n| logo = SEPTACityTrolley.svg\n| logo_width = 100px\n| logo_alt = Logo for SEPTA's subway\u2013surface trolley lines\n| image = File:SEPTA Subway-Surface underground.jpg\n| image_width = 300px\n| image_alt = Route 11 trolley at [[19th Street station (SEPTA)|19th Street station]]\n| caption = Route 11 trolley at [[19th Street station (SEPTA)|19th Street station]]\n<!-- Overview ----- ----- -->\n| other_name = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| type = [[Tram|Trolley]]\n| system = [[SEPTA|SEPTA City Transit Division]]\n| status = \n| locale = [[Philadelphia]], [[Yeadon, Pennsylvania|Yeadon]], and [[Darby, Pennsylvania|Darby]], [[Pennsylvania|PA]]\n| coordinates = \n| start = [[Overbrook Loop (SEPTA station)|Overbrook]] (Route 10)<br>[[Darby Transportation Center|Darby]] (Routes 11, 13)<br />[[Angora Loop (SEPTA station)|Angora]] (Route 34)<br />[[Eastwick Loop (SEPTA station)|Eastwick]] (Route 36)\n| end = [[13th Street (SEPTA station)|13th Street]] (all lines)\n| stations = 8 underground stations,<br>8 major surface stations\n| routes = [[SEPTA Route 10|Route 10]] (Lancaster Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 11|Route 11]] (Woodland Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 13|Route 13]] (Chester Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 34|Route 34]] (Baltimore Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 36|Route 36]] (Elmwood Avenue)\n| daily_ridership = 132,255\n| ridership2 = \n| trainnumber = 10, 11, 13, 34, 36\n| linenumber = \n| mapcolorlink = \n| mapcolor = \n| website = {{URL|septa.org/service/trolley}}\n<!-- Operation ----- ----- -->\n| open = {{Start date|1906}}\n| close = \n| reopen = \n| owner = [[SEPTA]]\n| operator = [[SEPTA]] \n| character = Underground and surface\n| depot = [[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]], [[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n| stock = [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]] K LRV cars\n<!-- Events ----- ----- -->\n| event1label = \n| event1 = \n| event2label = \n| event2 = \n| event3label = \n| event3 = \n<!-- Technical ----- ----- -->\n| linelength = {{convert|63.7|km|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Railopenings\" />\n| linelength_footnotes = \n| tracklength = \n| tracklength_footnotes = \n| tracks = \n| gauge = [[Pennsylvania gauge|PA gauge]]: {{Track gauge|5ft2.25in}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillytrolley.org/1974history/2-3.html|page=2|title=The history of trolley cars and routes in Philadelphia|publisher=[[SEPTA]]|date=June 1, 1974|accessdate=2014-06-11|quote=An early city ordinance prescribed that all tracks were to have a gauge of 5' {{frac|2|1|4}}.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first1=George W.|last1=Hilton|first2=John Fitzgerald|last2=Due |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J2zH-zcuU-MC&pg=PA51 |title=The Electric Interurban Railways in America|publisher=Stanford University Press|date=January 1, 2000|accessdate=2014-06-10|quote=Worst of all, not all city systems were built to the standard American and European gauge of 4'-{{frac|8|1|2}}\". Pittsburgh and most other Pennsylvania cities used 5'-{{frac|2|1|2}}\", which became known as the Pennsylvania trolley gauge. Cincinnati used 5'-{{frac|2|1|2}}\", Philadelphia 5'-{{frac|2|1|4}}\", Columbus 5'-2\", Altoona 5'-3\", Louisville and Camden 5'-0\", Canton and Pueblo 4'-0\", Denver, Tacoma, and Los Angeles 3'-6\", Toronto an odd 4'-{{frac|10|7|8}}\", and Baltimore a vast 5'-{{frac|4|1|2}}.}}</ref>\n| old_gauge = \n| load_gauge = \n| availability = \n| minradius = \n| electrification = [[Overhead line]]\n| speed = \n| signalling = \n| elevation = \n| maxincline = \n| racksystem = \n| routenumber = \n| aveinterstation = \n<!-- Routemap ----- ----- -->\n| map = {{SEPTA Subway-Surface Lines}}\n| map_state = \n}}\n\nThe '''SEPTA subway\u2013surface trolley lines''' are a collection of five [[Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority|SEPTA]] [[tram|trolley]] lines that operate on street-level [[Tramway track|tracks]] in [[West Philadelphia]] and [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania]], and also underneath [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]] in [[Philadelphia]]'s [[Center City, Philadelphia|Center City]]. The lines, '''Routes 10, 11, 13, 34, and 36''', collectively operate on about {{convert|39.6|mi|km}} of route.<ref name=\"Railopenings\">{{cite web | url=http://www.septa.org/ | last=Smith, Jr. | first=Bill W. | title=U.S. Urban Rail Transit Lines Opened From 1980 | website=SEPTA.org | pages = 1-100 | format=pdf | date=November 2011 | accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref>\n\nSEPTA's [[SEPTA Route 15|Route 15]], the [[Girard Avenue]] Line, is another streetcar line that is designated green on route maps but is not part of the subway\u2013surface system.\n\nLike [[Boston]]'s [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]] and [[San Francisco]]'s [[Muni Metro]], the SEPTA trolley line is the descendant of a pre-World War II streetcar system. Where Boston and San Francisco's systems use longer, articulated [[light rail|LRT]] vehicles, Philadelphia uses rigid vehicles roughly four inches longer than the [[PCC streetcar]] they somewhat replaced. The lines use [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]] K-Car LRVs delivered in 1981-82. The cars are similar to those on [[SEPTA Routes 101 and 102|Routes 101 and 102]], SEPTA's suburban trolley routes, which were delivered around the same time. However, the subway\u2013surface cars are single-ended and use [[trolley pole]]s, while the suburban lines use double ended cars and [[Pantograph (transport)|pantographs]] for power collection.\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Center City===\nStarting from their eastern terminus at [[13th Street station (SEPTA)|13th Street Station]] near [[City Hall (Philadelphia)|City Hall]], the trolleys loop around in a tunnel under City Hall before stopping at under [[Dilworth Park]] at [[15th Street station (SEPTA)|15th Street station]] and then realign back under [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]].\n\nAll five routes also stop at [[19th Street (SEPTA station)|19th Street]], [[22nd Street (SEPTA station)|22nd Street]], [[30th Street station (subway)|30th Street]], and [[33rd Street (SEPTA station)|33rd Street]], which are all underground stations. From 15th to 30th Streets, they run in the same tunnel as SEPTA's [[Market\u2013Frankford Line]], which runs express on the inner tracks while the trolleys utilize the outer ones.\n\nPassengers may transfer free of charge to the Market\u2013Frankford Line at 13th, 15th, and 30th Streets, as well as to the [[Broad Street Line]] at 15th Street. Connections to the [[SEPTA Regional Rail|Regional Rail]] are also available via underground passageways connecting 13th and 15th Street stations to [[Suburban Station]], one of the city's main commuter rail terminals.\n\n===University City===\nAfter traveling under the [[Schuylkill River]], the trolley lines provide access to [[30th Street Station]], a passenger terminal located across the street from the trolley and rapid transit station. Connection is available to Regional Rail, many [[Amtrak]] services, and [[New Jersey Transit]]'s [[Atlantic City Line]]. An underground passageway that connects these two stations is currently closed. {{citation needed|date=February 2018}} The closure was due to passenger safety issues after a passenger attack in the 1990s. In 2016, the 30th Street Station District proposed overhauling both 30th Street Station's SEPTA and trolley stations including, by public demand, the reopening the tunnel that connects the two (currently separate) stations, thus ceasing the need for passengers to resurface, walk outside to cross the busy 30th Street, and then enter the other station. The timeline called for the tunnel overhaul to be part of Phase 1 and thus completed by 2020. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://planphilly.com/articles/2016/03/15/30th-street-station-district-draft-plan-reopen-septa-tunnel-by-2020-cap-rail-yards-by-2050|title=30th Street Station District draft plan: Reopen SEPTA tunnel by 2020, cap rail yards by 2050|work=PlanPhilly {{!}} 30th Street Station District draft plan: Reopen SEPTA tunnel by 2020, cap rail yards by 2050|access-date=2018-07-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAll routes then stop at 33rd Street, near Drexel University. After this stop, Route 10 diverts from the others and emerges from the tunnel at the [[36th Street Portal]] just south of Market Street, then turns north onto 36th Street and then northwest along [[Lancaster Avenue]] and other surface streets. The other four lines make underground stops at [[36th Street station (SEPTA)|36th and Sansom streets]] and [[37th Street station (SEPTA)|37th and Spruce streets]] on the campus of the [[University of Pennsylvania]] before surfacing at the [[40th Street Portal]] near [[Baltimore Avenue]], heading southwest on surface streets.\n\n===Points south and west===\n{{expand section|date=February 2018}}\nThe Route 11 line travels along Woodland Avenue in Philadelphia and Main Street in [[Darby, Pennsylvania|Darby]]. It crosses a [[CSX Transportation]] railroad line at grade, one of very few at-grade crossing between a trolley line and a major freight rail line in the United States. (Another belongs to the [[TECO Line Streetcar System|TECO streetcar]] system in [[Tampa, Florida]].)<ref>[http://ktransit.com/transit/NAmerica/useast/philadelphia/lightrail/phl-lr-rt11.htm Philadelphia Transit; Streetcars;Route 11 (Kavanaugh Transit Systems)]</ref><ref>{{cite video |people=[https://www.flickr.com/people/32693718@N07 davidwilson1949] |date=July 6, 2003 |title=20030706 26 Main St. Crossing CSXT in Darby (6071320235) |url= https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:20030706_26_Main_St._Crossing_CSXT_in_Darby_(6071320235).jpg |medium= photograph |accessdate= December 31, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Diversion services===\nAll five trolleys can be diverted onto auxiliary surface tracks west of the [[40th Street Portal]] when tunnels are closed due to maintenance, an accident, or some other obstruction.\n\nTracks for Route 10 start at Lancaster Avenue (Route 10) and proceed southbound along 40th Street. At [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]], the line connects to the [[Market\u2013Frankford Line]] at its [[40th Street station (SEPTA)|40th Street station]]. The surface tracks continue southbound to [[Spruce Street (Philadelphia)|Spruce Street]], where they split either eastbound or westbound. Westbound tracks run to 42nd Street where they turn south to either Baltimore Avenue (Route 34), Chester Avenue (Route 13), or Woodland Avenue (Routes 11 and 36).\n\nTracks for the other four routes run northbound along 42nd Street, then turning east onto Spruce Street and then north onto 38th Street ([[U.S. Route 13 in Pennsylvania|US 13]]). From here, it travels to Filbert Street, then turning left and crossing the 40th Street tracks. When Filbert Street terminates at 41st Street, the tracks turn right, and head north until reaching Lancaster Avenue.<ref>[http://www.septa.org/maps/trolley/city.html SEPTA trolley lines map]</ref>\n\nAnother set of diversionary trolley tracks begin near the [[49th Street station (SEPTA Regional Rail)|49th Street Regional Rail station]], connecting Chester Avenue to Woodland Avenue (where Routes 11 and 36 separate) by way of 49th Street.\n\n==History==\n[[File:University of Pennsylvania College Hall.jpg|right|thumb|[[College Hall (University of Pennsylvania)|College Hall]] and Logan Hall on the campus of the [[University of Pennsylvania]], as viewed from Woodland Avenue c. 1892.]]\n[[File:SEPTA Subway-Surface map.png|thumb|Schematic map of subway\u2013surface branches and termini]]\nThe subway\u2013surface lines are remnants of the far more extensive streetcar system that developed in Philadelphia after the arrival of electric trolleys in 1892. Several dozen traction companies were consolidated in 1902 into the Philadelphia Rapid Transit Company. The PRT funneled the West Philadelphia lines into subway tunnels as they approached the city center. After the PRT declared bankruptcy in 1939, it was reopened as the [[Philadelphia Transportation Company]] (PTC), which was absorbed into SEPTA in 1968.<ref name=\"route34\">{{cite web| url=http://studio34yoga.com/about-us/our-trolley/ | title=Studio 34's Eponymous Trolley, or, A Short History of Route 34 | accessdate=2008-03-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, [[University of Pennsylvania]]'s class of 1956 funded the construction of an innovative portal for one of the eastbound entrances of the [[37th Street station (SEPTA)|37th Street station]]: a replica of a [[Peter Witt streetcar|Peter Witt]] trolley of the kind manufactured by [[J. G. Brill and Company]] from 1923\u201326. Operated by the Philadelphia Transportation Company, these trolleys brought university students to the campus and to [[Center City, Philadelphia|Center City]] until 1956. Routes 11, 34 and 37 ran through the Penn campus on Woodland Avenue and Locust Streets for nearly 65 years. In 1956, the trolley route was buried to enable the university to unify its campus, with Woodland Avenue and Locust Street becoming pedestrian walkways.\n\n==Routes==\nAll routes terminate at [[15th Street station (SEPTA)|15th Street station]] between 12:30 a.m. and 5:00 a.m. when 13th Street is closed. On Sunday evenings and during unexpected diversions, all routes are diverted to surface streets and terminate at [[40th Street station (SEPTA)|40th Street station]]. Former trolley routes, which have since been replaced with [[SEPTA City Bus|bus service]], are shaded in gray.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Route\n!Length in<br>{{nowrap|miles (km)<ref name=\"SEPTA-Stats\">{{cite web | title = SEPTA - Spring 2012 Route Statistics | publisher = Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority | url = http://www.septa.org/reports/pdf/route-statistics.pdf | year = 2012 | accessdate = 2013-06-28}}</ref>}}\n!Service began\n!Service ended\n!Western terminus\n!Eastern terminus\n!Main streets of travel\n!Depot\n!Notes\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 10|10]]\n|5.9 (9.5)\n|{{circa|1887}}\n|\n|[[Overbrook, Philadelphia|Overbrook]]: [[63rd Street and Malvern Avenue station|63rd\u2013Malvern]]\n|rowspan=9|[[Center City, Philadelphia|Center City]]:<br>[[15th Street station (SEPTA)|15th\u2013Market]] (12:30-5:00am)<br>{{nowrap|[[40th Street station (SEPTA)|40th\u2013Market]] (Sundays after 10pm)}}<br>[[13th Street station (SEPTA)|13th\u2013Market]] (all other times)\n|63rd Street, Lansdowne Avenue, Lancaster Avenue\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 11|11]]\n|6.7 (10.8)\n|1858\n|\n|rowspan=2|[[Darby, Pennsylvania|Darby]] [[Darby Transportation Center|Transportation Center]]\n|Woodland Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 13|13]]\n|6.9 (11.1)\n|\n|\n|Chester Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|Some trips terminate at [[Yeadon Loop station|Yeadon Loop]] in [[Yeadon, Pennsylvania|Yeadon]]\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 30|30]]\n|\n|\n|1915\n|[[Haddington, Philadelphia|Haddington]]: 65th & Vine Streets\n|Haverford Avenue, Vine Street\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|Rerouted\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 31|31]]\n|\n|\n|1956\n|[[Overbrook Park, Philadelphia|Overbrook Park]]: Lansdowne & Haverford Avenues Loop\n|63rd Street, Market Street\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|Replaced by bus service\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 34|34]]\n|4.8 (7.7)\n|1890\n|\n|[[Angora, Philadelphia|Angora]]: [[61st Street station (SEPTA)|61st\u2013Baltimore]]\n|Baltimore Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 36|36]]\n| 7.0 (11.3)\n|1904\n|\n|[[Eastwick, Philadelphia|Eastwick]]: [[80th Street-Eastwick station|80th\u2013Eastwick]]\n|Island Avenue, Elmwood Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|Some trips terminate at [[73rd Street station|73rd\u2013Elmwood]] station in [[Eastwick, Philadelphia|Eastwick]]\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 37|37]]\n|\n|\n|1955\n|[[Chester, Pennsylvania|Chester]]: 3rd & Crosby Streets\n|[[Pennsylvania Route 291|Industrial Highway]], Eastwick Avenue, Woodland Avenue \n|[[Woodland Carhouse|Woodland]]\n|Replaced by bus service\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 38|38]]\n|\n|\n|1955\n|[[Parkside, Philadelphia|Parkside]]: 48th Street & Parkside Avenue Loop\n|Parkside Avenue, 40th Street, Baring Street\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|Replaced by bus service\n|}\n[[File:septa34trolley.jpg|thumb|300px|The interior of a Route 34 trolley in the Center City Tunnel.]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia}}\n* [[Pennsylvania gauge]]\n*[[SEPTA City Transit Division surface routes]]\n*[[West Philadelphia Streetcar Suburb Historic District]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n{{Commons category|SEPTA Subway-Surface Trolley Lines}}\n*[http://www.septa.org/schedules/trolley/index.html SEPTA subway and trolley schedules]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080309002905/http://www.facilities.upenn.edu/mapsBldgs/view_map.php3?id=194 Map of subway\u2013surface lines in West Philadelphia]\n*[http://www.publictransit.us/ptlibrary/trafficdensity/data/PPhiladelphia.htm Tramway, Light Railway and LRT in Philadelphia (PublicTransit.US)]\n*[http://www.chicagorailfan.com/phlhisc.html Transit Systems in Philadelphia] and [http://www.chicagorailfan.com/maptijpe.html Southeast Pennsylvania Electric Railway map (Chicago Railfan.net)]\n*[http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/SEPTA_Subway-Surface_Streetcar_Lines WorldNYCSubway.org \u2013 SEPTA Subway\u2013Surface Streetcar Lines]\n*[http://subway-surface-improvements.webnode.com/ A Better Subway Surface System]\n\n{{SEPTA |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Delaware Valley transit}}\n{{USLightRail}}\n{{Legacy Streetcars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Septa Subway-Surface Trolley Lines}}\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1906]]\n[[Category:SEPTA]]\n[[Category:SEPTA Light Rail|Subway-Surface Trolley Lines]]\n[[Category:SEPTA Rapid Transit|Subway-Surface Trolley Lines]]\n[[Category:SEPTA Subway\u2013Surface Trolley| ]]\n[[Category:Light rail in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Underground rapid transit in the United States]]\n[[Category:5 ft 2\u00bc in gauge railways in the United States]]\n[[Category:600 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Green Line (Philadelphia)|other green lines|Green Line (disambiguation){{!}}Green Line|the proposed rail system|Greenline (Pennsylvania)}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name = Subway\u2013surface trolley lines<br><small>Routes 10, 11, 13, 34, 36</small>\n<!-- Styles ----- ----- -->\n| box_width = auto\n| color = {{rcr|SEPTA|Subway-Surface}}\n<!-- Images ----- ----- -->\n| logo = SEPTACityTrolley.svg\n| logo_width = 100px\n| logo_alt = Logo for SEPTA's subway\u2013surface trolley lines\n| image = File:SEPTA Subway-Surface underground.jpg\n| image_width = 300px\n| image_alt = Route 11 trolley at [[19th Street station (SEPTA)|19th Street station]]\n| caption = Route 11 trolley at [[19th Street station (SEPTA)|19th Street station]]\n<!-- Overview ----- ----- -->\n| other_name = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| type = [[Tram|Trolley]]\n| system = [[SEPTA|SEPTA City Transit Division]]\n| status = \n| locale = [[Philadelphia]], [[Yeadon, Pennsylvania|Yeadon]], and [[Darby, Pennsylvania|Darby]], [[Pennsylvania|PA]]\n| coordinates = \n| start = [[Overbrook Loop (SEPTA station)|Overbrook]] (Route 10)<br>[[Darby Transportation Center|Darby]] (Routes 11, 13)<br />[[Angora Loop (SEPTA station)|Angora]] (Route 34)<br />[[Eastwick Loop (SEPTA station)|Eastwick]] (Route 36)\n| end = [[13th Street (SEPTA station)|13th Street]] (all lines)\n| stations = 8 underground stations,<br>8 major surface stations\n| routes = [[SEPTA Route 10|Route 10]] (Lancaster Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 11|Route 11]] (Woodland Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 13|Route 13]] (Chester Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 34|Route 34]] (Baltimore Avenue)<br>[[SEPTA Route 36|Route 36]] (Elmwood Avenue)\n| daily_ridership = 132,255\n| ridership2 = \n| trainnumber = 10, 11, 13, 34, 36\n| linenumber = \n| mapcolorlink = \n| mapcolor = \n| website = {{URL|septa.org/service/trolley}}\n<!-- Operation ----- ----- -->\n| open = {{Start date|1906}}\n| close = \n| reopen = \n| owner = [[SEPTA]]\n| operator = [[SEPTA]] \n| character = Underground and surface\n| depot = [[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]], [[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n| stock = [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]] K LRV cars\n<!-- Events ----- ----- -->\n| event1label = \n| event1 = \n| event2label = \n| event2 = \n| event3label = \n| event3 = \n<!-- Technical ----- ----- -->\n| linelength = {{convert|63.7|km|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Railopenings\" />\n| linelength_footnotes = \n| tracklength = \n| tracklength_footnotes = \n| tracks = \n| gauge = [[Pennsylvania gauge|PA gauge]]: {{Track gauge|5ft2.25in}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillytrolley.org/1974history/2-3.html|page=2|title=The history of trolley cars and routes in Philadelphia|publisher=[[SEPTA]]|date=June 1, 1974|accessdate=2014-06-11|quote=An early city ordinance prescribed that all tracks were to have a gauge of 5' {{frac|2|1|4}}.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first1=George W.|last1=Hilton|first2=John Fitzgerald|last2=Due |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J2zH-zcuU-MC&pg=PA51 |title=The Electric Interurban Railways in America|publisher=Stanford University Press|date=January 1, 2000|accessdate=2014-06-10|quote=Worst of all, not all city systems were built to the standard American and European gauge of 4'-{{frac|8|1|2}}\". Pittsburgh and most other Pennsylvania cities used 5'-{{frac|2|1|2}}\", which became known as the Pennsylvania trolley gauge. Cincinnati used 5'-{{frac|2|1|2}}\", Philadelphia 5'-{{frac|2|1|4}}\", Columbus 5'-2\", Altoona 5'-3\", Louisville and Camden 5'-0\", Canton and Pueblo 4'-0\", Denver, Tacoma, and Los Angeles 3'-6\", Toronto an odd 4'-{{frac|10|7|8}}\", and Baltimore a vast 5'-{{frac|4|1|2}}.}}</ref>\n| old_gauge = \n| load_gauge = \n| availability = \n| minradius = \n| electrification = [[Overhead line]]\n| speed = \n| signalling = \n| elevation = \n| maxincline = \n| racksystem = \n| routenumber = \n| aveinterstation = \n<!-- Routemap ----- ----- -->\n| map = {{SEPTA Subway-Surface Lines}}\n| map_state = \n}}\n\nThe '''SEPTA subway\u2013surface trolley lines''' are a collection of five [[Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority|SEPTA]] [[tram|trolley]] lines that operate on street-level [[Tramway track|tracks]] in [[West Philadelphia]] and [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania]], and also underneath [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]] in [[Philadelphia]]'s [[Center City, Philadelphia|Center City]]. The lines, '''Routes 10, 11, 13, 34, and 36''', collectively operate on about {{convert|39.6|mi|km}} of route.<ref name=\"Railopenings\">{{cite web | url=http://www.septa.org/ | last=Smith, Jr. | first=Bill W. | title=U.S. Urban Rail Transit Lines Opened From 1980 | website=SEPTA.org | pages = 1-100 | format=pdf | date=November 2011 | accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref>\n\nSEPTA's [[SEPTA Route 15|Route 15]], the [[Girard Avenue]] Line, is another streetcar line that is designated green on route maps but is not part of the subway\u2013surface system.\n\nLike [[Boston]]'s [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]] and [[San Francisco]]'s [[Muni Metro]], the SEPTA trolley line is the descendant of a pre-World War II streetcar system. Where Boston and San Francisco's systems use longer, articulated [[light rail|LRT]] vehicles, Philadelphia uses rigid vehicles roughly four inches longer than the [[PCC streetcar]] they somewhat replaced. The lines use [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]] K-Car LRVs delivered in 1981-82. The cars are similar to those on [[SEPTA Routes 101 and 102|Routes 101 and 102]], SEPTA's suburban trolley routes, which were delivered around the same time. However, the subway\u2013surface cars are single-ended and use [[trolley pole]]s, while the suburban lines use double ended cars and [[Pantograph (transport)|pantographs]] for power collection.\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Center City===\nStarting from their eastern terminus at [[13th Street station (SEPTA)|13th Street Station]] near [[City Hall (Philadelphia)|City Hall]], the trolleys loop around in a tunnel under City Hall before stopping at under [[Dilworth Park]] at [[15th Street station (SEPTA)|15th Street station]] and then realign back under [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]].\n\nAll five routes also stop at [[19th Street (SEPTA station)|19th Street]], [[22nd Street (SEPTA station)|22nd Street]], [[30th Street station (subway)|30th Street]], and [[33rd Street (SEPTA station)|33rd Street]], which are all underground stations. From 15th to 30th Streets, they run in the same tunnel as SEPTA's [[Market\u2013Frankford Line]], which runs express on the inner tracks while the trolleys utilize the outer ones.\n\nPassengers may transfer free of charge to the Market\u2013Frankford Line at 13th, 15th, and 30th Streets, as well as to the [[Broad Street Line]] at 15th Street. Connections to the [[SEPTA Regional Rail|Regional Rail]] are also available via underground passageways connecting 13th and 15th Street stations to [[Suburban Station]], one of the city's main commuter rail terminals.\n\n===University City===\nAfter traveling under the [[Schuylkill River]], the trolley lines provide access to [[30th Street Station]], a passenger terminal located across the street from the trolley and rapid transit station. Connection is available to Regional Rail, many [[Amtrak]] services, and [[New Jersey Transit]]'s [[Atlantic City Line]]. An underground passageway that connects these two stations is currently closed. {{citation needed|date=February 2018}} The closure was due to passenger safety issues after a passenger attack in the 1990s. In 2016, the 30th Street Station District proposed overhauling both 30th Street Station's SEPTA and trolley stations including, by public demand, the reopening the tunnel that connects the two (currently separate) stations, thus ceasing the need for passengers to resurface, walk outside to cross the busy 30th Street, and then enter the other station. The timeline called for the tunnel overhaul to be part of Phase 1 and thus completed by 2020. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://planphilly.com/articles/2016/03/15/30th-street-station-district-draft-plan-reopen-septa-tunnel-by-2020-cap-rail-yards-by-2050|title=30th Street Station District draft plan: Reopen SEPTA tunnel by 2020, cap rail yards by 2050|work=PlanPhilly {{!}} 30th Street Station District draft plan: Reopen SEPTA tunnel by 2020, cap rail yards by 2050|access-date=2018-07-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAll routes then stop at 33rd Street, near Drexel University. After this stop, Route 10 diverts from the others and emerges from the tunnel at the [[36th Street Portal]] just south of Market Street, then turns north onto 36th Street and then northwest along [[Lancaster Avenue]] and other surface streets. The other four lines make underground stops at [[36th Street station (SEPTA)|36th and Sansom streets]] and [[37th Street station (SEPTA)|37th and Spruce streets]] on the campus of the [[University of Pennsylvania]] before surfacing at the [[40th Street Portal]] near [[Baltimore Avenue]], heading southwest on surface streets.\n\n===Points south and west===\n{{expand section|date=February 2018}}\nThe Route 11 line travels along Woodland Avenue in Philadelphia and Main Street in [[Darby, Pennsylvania|Darby]]. It crosses a [[CSX Transportation]] railroad line at grade, one of very few at-grade crossing between a trolley line and a major freight rail line in the United States. (Another belongs to the [[TECO Line Streetcar System|TECO streetcar]] system in [[Tampa, Florida]].)<ref>[http://ktransit.com/transit/NAmerica/useast/philadelphia/lightrail/phl-lr-rt11.htm Philadelphia Transit; Streetcars;Route 11 (Kavanaugh Transit Systems)]</ref><ref>{{cite video |people=[https://www.flickr.com/people/32693718@N07 davidwilson1949] |date=July 6, 2003 |title=20030706 26 Main St. Crossing CSXT in Darby (6071320235) |url= https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:20030706_26_Main_St._Crossing_CSXT_in_Darby_(6071320235).jpg |medium= photograph |accessdate= December 31, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Diversion services===\nAll five trolleys can be diverted onto auxiliary surface tracks west of the [[40th Street Portal]] when tunnels are closed due to maintenance, an accident, or some other obstruction.\n\nTracks for Route 10 start at Lancaster Avenue (Route 10) and proceed southbound along 40th Street. At [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]], the line connects to the [[Market\u2013Frankford Line]] at its [[40th Street station (SEPTA)|40th Street station]]. The surface tracks continue southbound to [[Spruce Street (Philadelphia)|Spruce Street]], where they splits either eastbound or westbound. Westbound tracks run to 42nd Street where they turn south to either Baltimore Avenue (Route 34), Chester Avenue (Route 13), or Woodland Avenue (Routes 11 and 36).\n\nTracks for the other four routes run northbound along 42nd Street, then turning east onto Spruce Street and then north onto 38th Street ([[U.S. Route 13 in Pennsylvania|US 13]]). From here, it travels to Filbert Street, then turning left and crossing the 40th Street tracks. When Filbert Street terminates at 41st Street, the tracks turn right, and head north until reaching Lancaster Avenue.<ref>[http://www.septa.org/maps/trolley/city.html SEPTA trolley lines map]</ref>\n\nAnother set of diversionary trolley tracks begin near the [[49th Street station (SEPTA Regional Rail)|49th Street Regional Rail station]], connecting Chester Avenue to Woodland Avenue (where Routes 11 and 36 separate) by way of 49th Street.\n\n==History==\n[[File:University of Pennsylvania College Hall.jpg|right|thumb|[[College Hall (University of Pennsylvania)|College Hall]] and Logan Hall on the campus of the [[University of Pennsylvania]], as viewed from Woodland Avenue c. 1892.]]\n[[File:SEPTA Subway-Surface map.png|thumb|Schematic map of subway\u2013surface branches and termini]]\nThe subway\u2013surface lines are remnants of the far more extensive streetcar system that developed in Philadelphia after the arrival of electric trolleys in 1892. Several dozen traction companies were consolidated in 1902 into the Philadelphia Rapid Transit Company. The PRT funneled the West Philadelphia lines into subway tunnels as they approached the city center. After the PRT declared bankruptcy in 1939, it was reopened as the [[Philadelphia Transportation Company]] (PTC), which was absorbed into SEPTA in 1968.<ref name=\"route34\">{{cite web| url=http://studio34yoga.com/about-us/our-trolley/ | title=Studio 34's Eponymous Trolley, or, A Short History of Route 34 | accessdate=2008-03-11 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, [[University of Pennsylvania]]'s class of 1956 funded the construction of an innovative portal for one of the eastbound entrances of the [[37th Street station (SEPTA)|37th Street station]]: a replica of a [[Peter Witt streetcar|Peter Witt]] trolley of the kind manufactured by [[J. G. Brill and Company]] from 1923\u201326. Operated by the Philadelphia Transportation Company, these trolleys brought university students to the campus and to [[Center City, Philadelphia|Center City]] until 1956. Routes 11, 34 and 37 ran through the Penn campus on Woodland Avenue and Locust Streets for nearly 65 years. In 1956, the trolley route was buried to enable the university to unify its campus, with Woodland Avenue and Locust Street becoming pedestrian walkways.\n\n==Routes==\nAll routes terminate at [[15th Street station (SEPTA)|15th Street station]] between 12:30 a.m. and 5:00 a.m. when 13th Street is closed. On Sunday evenings and during unexpected diversions, all routes are diverted to surface streets and terminate at [[40th Street station (SEPTA)|40th Street station]]. Former trolley routes, which have since been replaced with [[SEPTA City Bus|bus service]], are shaded in gray.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Route\n!Length in<br>{{nowrap|miles (km)<ref name=\"SEPTA-Stats\">{{cite web | title = SEPTA - Spring 2012 Route Statistics | publisher = Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority | url = http://www.septa.org/reports/pdf/route-statistics.pdf | year = 2012 | accessdate = 2013-06-28}}</ref>}}\n!Service began\n!Service ended\n!Western terminus\n!Eastern terminus\n!Main streets of travel\n!Depot\n!Notes\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 10|10]]\n|5.9 (9.5)\n|{{circa|1887}}\n|\n|[[Overbrook, Philadelphia|Overbrook]]: [[63rd Street and Malvern Avenue station|63rd\u2013Malvern]]\n|rowspan=9|[[Center City, Philadelphia|Center City]]:<br>[[15th Street station (SEPTA)|15th\u2013Market]] (12:30-5:00am)<br>{{nowrap|[[40th Street station (SEPTA)|40th\u2013Market]] (Sundays after 10pm)}}<br>[[13th Street station (SEPTA)|13th\u2013Market]] (all other times)\n|63rd Street, Lansdowne Avenue, Lancaster Avenue\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 11|11]]\n|6.7 (10.8)\n|1858\n|\n|rowspan=2|[[Darby, Pennsylvania|Darby]] [[Darby Transportation Center|Transportation Center]]\n|Woodland Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 13|13]]\n|6.9 (11.1)\n|\n|\n|Chester Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|Some trips terminate at [[Yeadon Loop station|Yeadon Loop]] in [[Yeadon, Pennsylvania|Yeadon]]\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 30|30]]\n|\n|\n|1915\n|[[Haddington, Philadelphia|Haddington]]: 65th & Vine Streets\n|Haverford Avenue, Vine Street\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|Rerouted\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 31|31]]\n|\n|\n|1956\n|[[Overbrook Park, Philadelphia|Overbrook Park]]: Lansdowne & Haverford Avenues Loop\n|63rd Street, Market Street\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|Replaced by bus service\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 34|34]]\n|4.8 (7.7)\n|1890\n|\n|[[Angora, Philadelphia|Angora]]: [[61st Street station (SEPTA)|61st\u2013Baltimore]]\n|Baltimore Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|\n|-\n![[SEPTA Route 36|36]]\n| 7.0 (11.3)\n|1904\n|\n|[[Eastwick, Philadelphia|Eastwick]]: [[80th Street-Eastwick station|80th\u2013Eastwick]]\n|Island Avenue, Elmwood Avenue\n|[[Elmwood Carhouse (SEPTA station)|Elmwood]]\n|Some trips terminate at [[73rd Street station|73rd\u2013Elmwood]] station in [[Eastwick, Philadelphia|Eastwick]]\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 37|37]]\n|\n|\n|1955\n|[[Chester, Pennsylvania|Chester]]: 3rd & Crosby Streets\n|[[Pennsylvania Route 291|Industrial Highway]], Eastwick Avenue, Woodland Avenue \n|[[Woodland Carhouse|Woodland]]\n|Replaced by bus service\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n![[SEPTA Route 38|38]]\n|\n|\n|1955\n|[[Parkside, Philadelphia|Parkside]]: 48th Street & Parkside Avenue Loop\n|Parkside Avenue, 40th Street, Baring Street\n|[[Callowhill Depot|Callowhill]]\n|Replaced by bus service\n|}\n[[File:septa34trolley.jpg|thumb|300px|The interior of a Route 34 trolley in the Center City Tunnel.]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia}}\n* [[Pennsylvania gauge]]\n*[[SEPTA City Transit Division surface routes]]\n*[[West Philadelphia Streetcar Suburb Historic District]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n{{Commons category|SEPTA Subway-Surface Trolley Lines}}\n*[http://www.septa.org/schedules/trolley/index.html SEPTA subway and trolley schedules]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080309002905/http://www.facilities.upenn.edu/mapsBldgs/view_map.php3?id=194 