{"title_page": "Siena Piano", "text_new": "{{Short description|Italian piano}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox instrument\n|name=Siena Piano\n|image=Siena Pianoforte 1868.jpg\n|caption=The Siena piano in 1868\n|classification=[[Chordophone]]\n|names=Immortal Piano<br>Harp of King David\n|related=[[Piano]], [[Fortepiano]]\n|musicians=[[Camille Saint-Sa\u00ebns]], [[Franz Liszt]], [[Charles Rosen]]<ref name=\"auctionhouse\"/>\n}}\nThe '''Siena Piano''', also called the '''Immortal Piano''' and the '''Harp of King David''', is a piano constructed at the beginning of the 19th century<ref name=\"auctionhouse\">{{Cite web|url=https://winners-auctions.com/en/content/immortal-piano-siena-turin-early-19th-century|title=The Immortal Piano of Siena. Turin, Early 19th Century {{!}} Winners Auctions|last=|first=|date=|website=Winners Auctions|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> that became famous in the 1950s for its remarkable sound and its unusual history. Its [[timbre]] is similar to both a piano and a [[harpsichord]]. Legend has it that it was partially built with wood from the pillars of the [[Solomon's Temple|Temple of Solomon]], because of its excellent sound and it being the spiritual descendant of the [[Harp of David]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/221-years-old-immortal-piano-to-go-under-the-hammer-likely-to-fetch-over-a-million-dollars/articleshow/74440619.cms|title=221-years-old 'Immortal Piano' to go under the hammer, likely to fetch over a million dollars|date=2020-03-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live|others=PTI}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">Catherine Rosenheimer (21 September 1979). [http://hfj.stparchive.com/Archive/HFJ/HFJ09211979P28.php The Million Dollar Piano]. Heritage Florida Jewish News. Accessed on 14 March 2020.</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://thejewishvoice.com/2020/03/piano-said-to-be-made-of-wood-from-jewish-temple-up-for-auction/|title=Piano Said to be Made of Wood from Jewish Temple Up for Auction|date=2020-03-07|website=The Jewish Voice|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Most critics say it is best for playing [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], [[Alessandro Scarlatti|Scarlatti]] and [[Claude Debussy|Debussy]].<ref name=\":0\">Ken and No\u00ebl Gilmore, (September 1960). [http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvintagevacuumaudio.com%2Fvintage-magazines%2Fhifi%2F1960-9-hifi-stereo-review.pdf \"The Fantastic Saga of the Siena Piano\"]. HiFi Stereo Review''.'' p. 60\u201366. Retrieved 14 March 2020.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1799, [[Turin]] harpsichord maker Sebastian Marchisio started constructing the piano but died before it was completed. His family completed the first build and it was later given as a wedding gift to Marchisio's granddaughter. Several modifications later it appeared at the [[Exposition Universelle (1867)|Paris World's Fair]] in 1867. It was then given as a wedding present by the city of [[Siena]] to the future king [[Umberto I of Italy]], after which it fell into Nazi possession.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/seized-by-nazis-found-in-israel-immortal-piano-expected-to-fetch-1m/|title=Seized by Nazis, found in Israel, 'Immortal Piano' expected to fetch $1m|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=|website=Times of Israel|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the defeat of the Germans by the British in the [[Battle of El Alamein]], 1942, the British found the piano, all plastered up, in a desert in North Africa.{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=237}} It was then used by some British entertainers who toured camps and sang for the wounded. It found a home at a [[Tel Aviv]] piano workshop belonging to Avner Carmi Yanowsky by way of an Israeli merchant.{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=243}}\n\nCarmi renovated the piano and he tried it out with several renowned musicians on tour in Israel. Pianist [[Pnina Salzman]] gave the first public recital of the Siena piano in Israel, a concert organized under the sponsorship of Prime Minister [[David Ben-Gurion]], on the day of the [[Israel's independence|declaration of Israel's independence]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The piano then toured Europe finally finding its way to the United States, where it was shown at [[Steinway Hall]] and used for recordings.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time the piano was extensively repaired again and again, the ancient crumbling sounding board giving way due to its age. During these times [[Sohmer & Co.|Sohmer Piano Company]] also decided to help Carmi with the repairs for over a year.<ref name=\":6\">Ken and No\u00ebl Gilmore, (September 1960). [http://fmera.org/CondonCollection/ARTICLES/HiFiArticle.pdf The Fantastic Saga of the Siena Piano]. HiFi Stereo Review''.'' pg 66. Accessed 14 March 2020.</ref> [[Marie-Jos\u00e9 of Belgium|Marie-Jose de Savoia]], after listening to the piano, gave her patronage for the piano to be played at a concert for the United Nations [[International Year of the Child]] in [[Jerusalem]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldpianonews.com/historical/art-case-historical/the-immortal-piano/|title=The Immortal Piano (aka The Siena Piano)|date=2020-01-10|website=World Piano News|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nCarmi and his wife wrote a book about the piano titled ''The Immortal Piano''. His daughter finally sold it in 1996 to a private collector for $1&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rhinegold.co.uk/international_piano/immortal-piano-offered-for-sale-online/|title='Immortal Piano' offered for sale online|website=Rhinegold|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The most recent owner, who lived in the town of [[Caesarea]], put the instrument up for auction in 2020.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"auctionhouse\" />\n\n== Description ==\nThe Siena piano is an [[upright piano]] with dual pedals whose wood carvings are characteristic of early 19th century Italy.<ref name=\":0\" /> The finishing touches and decorations on the piano were put on by Sebastian Marchisio's great-grandson, one of Italy's most famous craftsmen at the time, Nicomedo Ferri and a cousin. They engraved laughing, dancing, playing [[cherub]]s and other designs such as harps, pipes, faces and lions.<ref name=\":0\" /> Portraits of [[George Frideric Handel|H\u00e4ndel]], [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], [[Pietro Aretino|Aretino]], [[Cherubini]] and [[Christoph Willibald Gluck|Gluck]] were also made.{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=183, 198-200}} The front face of the underbody has a [[Bas-Relief|bas-relief panel]] decorated with [[arabesque]]s with a large laurel wreath in the middle of which is a [[harp of David]] surrounded by two [[griffin]]s.{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=184, 203}} On the lid the creators of the piano are written in Italian -  ''Fratelli Marchisio, Turino'' and ''Bartalozzi e Ferri, Siena.''{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=274}}\n\n[[Lazare L\u00e9vy]] said of the piano after performing a recital with it, \"This is the most astonishing piano I have come across. The works of [[Fran\u00e7ois Couperin|Couperin]] and [[Alessandro Scarlatti|Scarlatti]] sound as if they had been written especially for the Siena piano. And playing Bach and Mozart is much more interesting than any other piano I've ever played on...\"{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=12}}  American conductor and radio host [[David Randolph]] agreed that the piano sounds like a harpsichord at times and at other times like a lute, harp or guitar.<ref name=\":0\" /> Brazilian composer [[Heitor Villa-Lobos]] said \"I love the Immortal Piano, its sound and story equally\".<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Artur Schnabel]] said this is the story of a \"pianoman extraordinary, simply falling in love with the King's piano\".<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Recordings ==\n\n* ''The Siena Pianoforte, 1955'', six sonatas by [[Alessandro Scarlatti|Scarlatti]] and two sonatas by [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]] performed by [[Charles Rosen]], label Counterpoint/ Esoteric, Everest Records Production, CPT 3000/ 53000 (1958), Boston Skyline BSD 131 (1995).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200152723/|title=Charles Rosen|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n*''Bach on the Siena Pianoforte, 1956'', five compositions by [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]] including the ''[[Chaconne]]'' transcribed by [[Ferruccio Busoni|Busoni]], interpreted by [[Anatole Kitain]], label Counterpoint/ Esoteric, Everest Records Production, CPT 53001.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Siena pianoforte: Bach.|date=1955|publisher=Counterpoint/Esoteric|oclc=52863222}}</ref>\n*''A Recital of Spanish music on the Siena pianoforte'', ''1955'', compositions by [[Isaac Alb\u00e9niz|Alb\u00e9niz]], [[Federico Mompou|Mompou]], [[Joaqu\u00edn Turina|Turina]] and [[Heitor Villa-Lobos|Villa-Lobos]] by Marisa Regules, label Counterpoint/ Esoteric, Everest Records Production, CPT 53002.<ref>{{Citation|last=Regules|first=Marisa|title=A Recital of Spanish music on the Siena pianoforte|date=1955|url=http://archive.org/details/recitalofspanish00regu|others=Internet Archive|access-date=2020-03-15|last2=Turina|first2=Joaqu\u00edn|last3=Alb\u00e9niz|first3=Isaac|last4=Villa-Lobos|first4=Heitor Prole do beb\u00ea|last5=Mompou|first5=Federico|last6=Villa-Lobos|first6=Heitor Pr\u00f3le do b\u00e9b\u00e9}}</ref>\n*''The Siena Pianoforte'', Mozart sonatas and variations on a Gluck theme  by Kathryn Deguire, Counterpoint/ Esoteric label, Everest Records Production, CPT 53004.\n*''Christmas on the Siena Pianoforte, 1956'', nineteen Christmas tunes including [[Greensleeves]] and [[Adeste fideles|Adeste Fideles]] interpreted by Grace Castagnella, label Counterpoint / Esoteric, Everest Records Production, CPT 53005.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Castagnetta|first=Grace|title=Christmas on the Siena pianoforte|date=1956|publisher=Counterpoint/Esoteric Records|isbn=|location=Los Angeles|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{Cite book|last=Carmi|first=Avner|title=The Immortal Piano|last2=Carmi|first2=Hannah|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|year=1960|isbn=|location=New York|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Individual pianos]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Italian piano}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox instrument\n|name=Siena Piano\n|image=Siena Pianoforte 1868.jpg\n|caption=The Siena piano in 1868\n|classification=[[Chordophone]]\n|names=Immortal Piano<br>Harp of King David\n|related=[[Piano]], [[Fortepiano]]\n|musicians=[[Camille Saint-Sa\u00ebns]], [[Franz Liszt]], [[Charles Rosen]]<ref name=\"auctionhouse\"/>\n}}\nThe '''Siena Piano''', also called the '''Immortal Piano''' and the '''Harp of King David''', is a piano constructed at the beginning of the 19th century<ref name=\"auctionhouse\">{{Cite web|url=https://winners-auctions.com/en/content/immortal-piano-siena-turin-early-19th-century|title=The Immortal Piano of Siena. Turin, Early 19th Century {{!}} Winners Auctions|last=|first=|date=|website=Winners Auctions|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> that became famous in the 1950s for its remarkable sound and its unusual history. Its [[timbre]] is similar to both a piano and a [[harpsichord]]. Legend has it that it was partially built with wood from the pillars of the [[Solomon's Temple|Temple of Solomon]], because of its excellent sound and it being the spiritual descendant of the [[Harp of David]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/221-years-old-immortal-piano-to-go-under-the-hammer-likely-to-fetch-over-a-million-dollars/articleshow/74440619.cms|title=221-years-old 'Immortal Piano' to go under the hammer, likely to fetch over a million dollars|date=2020-03-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live|others=PTI}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">Catherine Rosenheimer (21 September 1979). [http://hfj.stparchive.com/Archive/HFJ/HFJ09211979P28.php The Million Dollar Piano]. Heritage Florida Jewish News. Accessed on 14 March 2020.</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://thejewishvoice.com/2020/03/piano-said-to-be-made-of-wood-from-jewish-temple-up-for-auction/|title=Piano Said to be Made of Wood from Jewish Temple Up for Auction|date=2020-03-07|website=The Jewish Voice|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Most critics say it is best for playing [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], [[Alessandro Scarlatti|Scarlatti]] and [[Claude Debussy|Debussy]].<ref name=\":0\">Ken and No\u00ebl Gilmore, (September 1960). [http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fvintagevacuumaudio.com%2Fvintage-magazines%2Fhifi%2F1960-9-hifi-stereo-review.pdf The Fantastic Saga of the Siena Piano]. HiFi Stereo Review''.'' pg 60 -66. Accessed 14 March 2020.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1799, [[Turin]] harpsichord maker Sebastian Marchisio started constructing the piano but died before it was completed. His family completed the first build and it was later given as a wedding gift to Marchisio's granddaughter. Several modifications later it appeared at the [[Exposition Universelle (1867)|Paris World's Fair]] in 1867. It was then given as a wedding present by the city of [[Siena]] to the future king [[Umberto I of Italy]], after which it fell into Nazi possession.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/seized-by-nazis-found-in-israel-immortal-piano-expected-to-fetch-1m/|title=Seized by Nazis, found in Israel, 'Immortal Piano' expected to fetch $1m|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=|website=Times of Israel|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the defeat of the Germans by the British in the [[Battle of El Alamein]], 1942, the British found the piano, all plastered up, in a desert in North Africa.{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=237}} It was then used by some British entertainers who toured camps and sang for the wounded. It found a home at a [[Tel Aviv]] piano workshop belonging to Avner Carmi Yanowsky by way of an Israeli merchant.{{Sfn|Carmi|Carmi|1960|p=243}}\n\nCarmi renovated the piano and he tried it out with several renowned musicians on tour in Israel. Pianist [[Pnina Salzman]] gave the first public recital of the Siena piano in Israel, a concert organized under the sponsorship of Prime Minister [[David Ben-Gurion]], on the day of the [[Israel's independence|declaration of Israel's independence]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The piano then toured Europe finally finding its way to the United States, where it was shown at [[Steinway Hall]] and used for recordings.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time the piano was extensively repaired again and again, the ancient crumbling sounding board giving way due to its age. During these times [[Sohmer & Co.|Sohmer Piano Company]] also decided to help Carmi with the repairs for over a year.<ref name=\":6\">Ken and No\u00ebl Gilmore, (September 1960). [http://fmera.org/CondonCollection/ARTICLES/HiFiArticle.pdf The Fantastic Saga of the Siena Piano]. HiFi Stereo Review''.'' pg 66. Accessed 14 March 2020.</ref> [[Marie-Jos\u00e9 of Belgium|Marie-Jose de Savoia]], after listening to the piano, gave her patronage for the piano to be played at a concert for the United Nations [[International Year of the Child]] in [[Jerusalem]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldpianonews.com/historical/art-case-historical/the-immortal-piano/|title=The Immortal Piano (aka The Siena Piano)|date=2020-01-10|website=World Piano News|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nCarmi and his wife wrote a book about the piano titled ''The Immortal Piano''. His daughter finally sold it